Curricular Materials - Cuban Social Class | CLACS | NYU                             NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                           Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies                            Back to Home         Printer Friendly       Curricular Materials - Perspectives on the Cuban Revolution: Social class, equality of opportunity and equality of outcomes before and after the Cuban Revolution The materials in this curricular unit enable educators to   - teach about life in Cuba before and after the Cuban Revolution from the perspective of different social classes   - teach students essential skills required to complete independent research projects      The primary essential question addressed in this unit is: What role should the government play in keeping society safe and fair? Educators can then explore more broadly the role and purposes of government, a topic of particular relevance in classrooms with immigrant students who can compare and contrast case studies from different countries.      Through the activities in this unit, students are assigned a particular social class perspective and use the lens of that social class to evaluate the revolution. They present these perspectives to each other in the form of a powerpoint presentation, and teach each other the key concepts pertaining to pre-revolution Cuba, Cuba during the revolution, and post-revolution Cuba. If time allows, students can then interview a peer/community member about what role government should play in contemporary United States, which would support the writing of an analytical essay comparing answers to this unit's essential question from post-Revolution Cuba and contemporary United States.      These materials were created in 2011 by Ariela Rothstein, an educator at the East Brooklyn Community High School, as part of the CLACS Teacher Residency Program.
